August 25 at 1:14 PM ·

Ward 5 —

The 2020-2021 School Year is officially underway! Let's be sure to celebrate our students and ensure they have the resources to effectively learn, whether it be through distance or in-person instruction, at this year's Ward 5 Back-to-School Supplies Giveaway!

If your Ward 5 student needs school supplies, please pick them up on September 11th via the McKinley Tech parking lot. All Ward 5 DCPS and charter students are eligible!

If you are in a position to donate, please do! All donations are tax deductible and 100% of donations will go to purchasing supplies.

DONATE HERE: https://www.paypal.com/donate/?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=2CUN66GDRM7D2

You can also find the link to donate at ward5eec.org or donate directly from the PayPal app to @Ward5BacktoSchool
Donations are received by McKinley Education Campus PTO, a 501 (c)(3).
!
Reach out to me with any questions!

Thank you!

#InvestIn5

Our team invites all members of the community to join us in celebrating our success by completing your own virtual 5K! This can be walking, biking, running, skipping, or rolling. Join us by sharing your good wishes to our team on social media, or posting photos of you and your family being active. #GOTRDC

post_text:
Today is a powerful day. Strong winds blow, and mighty trees are falling.

It is with the heaviest of heart that we share the news of a Mighty Oak Tree that has fallen. Today our beloved Mr. Philip Izlar, Sr., better known as PC suffered a heart attack and has earned his heavenly wings.

Mr. PC was usually the first person to greet families as they would drop their children off at school. And he would always greet every person with a smile. And oh what a smile it was. Mr. PC found the good in every human being that he came across. He had a heart of gold. He would take care of others before taking care of himself. PC was a man of ineffable sweetness, a constant source of unabashed love and unashamed joy in a world that rarely appreciates such qualities. His was the beating heart of a community. But that heart has come to a stop.

We cannot express how deeply sad we are as individuals and as a community. We are heartbroken, and we will not be able to function as normal tomorrow, and so school will be closed Friday, April 10, 2020.

Please take care.

post_text:
Good morning,

At Stokes School the safety and well-being of our students and staff is always our top priority. As we have watched the spread of the Coronavirus (COVID-19) in the United States over the past few weeks, we have also been developing contingency plans for the possibility of closing our campuses. In accordance with guidance from the Mayor of the District of Columbia’s office, the Elsie Whitlow Stokes Community Freedom Public Charter School will close beginning Monday, March 16th and remain closed through at least March 31st.

As we have previously communicated, Stokes School’s teachers and instructional staff are compiling materials that will facilitate student learning at home while our campuses are closed. We will provide specific information on how to access these materials in a subsequent communication with families.

Stokes School will continue to follow the guidance of federal and city government officials to determine when the school will re-open. We appreciate your cooperation and will keep you updated as soon as decisions are made.

Please be safe.

shared_text:
Elsie Whitlow Stokes Community Freedom PCS- Brookland Campus
March 8 at 8:48 PM ·

Dear Stokes School Community,

We are working to maintain a safe, healthy environment within our school community. We reiterate daily with staff and scholars the importance of:

proper hand washing;
avoiding touching eyes, noses and mouths;
sneezing/coughing in elbows or tissue; and
staying at home when we are ill.
Additionally, our cleaning company follows CDC recommendations for cleaning and disinfecting our buildings.

Despite these steps, there may still be a Coronavirus outbreak in Washington, DC. We are preparing for the possibility that the DC government may close the schools.

As we plan, we are working to ensure that staff has remote access to work and that scholars have access to learning. We ask that you complete this brief survey about your children's access to technology at home. https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdltRY-zX2NFZLOPjd4OUjIa85w0eIxsN3Xqkkk_jehcEGezw/viewform

To have adequate time to prepare, we ask that families submit responses by 5:00 pm on Tuesday, March 9th. Please feel free to reach out to any school administrator if you have questions.

post_text:
Big thanks to Casey Trees for their generous donation of a dogwood tree to replace a dead tree in our garden! Parents from Kindergarten French and Spanish worked together to remove the dead tree and plant the new one.

DID YOU KNOW? Trees have been an integral part of D.C. since Pierre L’Enfant’s original plans in the 1790’s. More recently, D.C. has earned the recognition as “Tree City USA” since 1991. Trees provide significant benefit in combating climate change by cleaning the air, absorbing storm water, and creating shade.

REMEMBER: This Saturday, Oct. 26th from 10:00AM-12:30PM, join the Brookland Stokes Community at our annual “Taste of Stokes” celebration. The Taste of Stokes event celebrates the work of our school’s health and wellness program as well as the community partnerships that support that program. You will be able to sample food from community food vendors, including our very own Stokes Kitchen. There will be opportunities during the event to learn more about gardening, composting, and wellness.

We hope you can join us!

post_text: On Monday, the fifth grade traveled to Elizabeth Furnace Campground in Virginia to embark on a Freshwater Snorkeling Trip. While snorkeling, students observed stream life to better understand the relationship between aquatic animals, aquatic habitat, and water quality. Additionally, our fifth graders collected water bugs from the river using nets and investigated water quality based on the types of bugs collected. It was a fantastic way to wrap up our Unit of Inquiry in which students studied "Webs of Life." WE feel very grateful to have experienced this trip together! -Ms. Ritinski (5th Grade English)

post_text:
As momentum for End The List grows, it is time for us to take action, and make our first move together! We have stated the issues, made our presence felt, and reached thousands of potential partners through our radio, television, and digital media campaigns. Allies are asking us, “So, what do we do now?!”

The next step, our first collective action, is to begin to get signatures on a petition that defines our purpose and states our Call to our Mayor for a win-win-win solution.

The Call is to release vacant and underutilized school buildings to high-performing charter schools as a win-win-win solution in which: DC families can get off charter school waiting lists; charter facilities funds can go to city-owned properties; DCPS schools can get rental revenue for programs in under-utilized buildings; abandoned buildings can be renovated and used as community assets; and DCPS and charter schools can collaborate in the interests of DC families.

post_text: Elsie Whitlow Stokes School founder, Linda Moore has recently been appointed to serve on the District of Columbia Association for the Education of Young Children (DCAEYC) Public Policy Committee. DCAEYC, the local affiliate of the National Association for the Education of Young Children, is a professional membership organization that works to promote high quality early learning for all young children, birth through age 8, connecting early childhood practice, policy and research. Ms. Moore also serves on the State Early Childhood Development Coordinating Council and the Office of the State Superintendent of Education Division of Early Learning’s Dual Language Learning Working Group.

post_text: We hope you had a great snow day! Stokes School will open tomorrow at 10:00 AM for all students. There will be no before care, but breakfast will be available at 10. All students should come through the Otis Street entrance tomorrow due to the icy conditions. Have a good evening, and please be safe.
